 <subsection><title>Many Ways to Write the Same Answer</title>
  <p> 
    Because of trigonometric identities, two expressions might look very different but actually be the same. 
    It is sometimes not that easy to determine if two expressions are equivalent or not.  
    This can cause some problems for example if you have worked on a problem and think you have a final answer, but your answer looks different from the answer given in some solution manual.   
  </p>

  <example ><title>NEED EXAMPLE</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      p. 691 ex 35-52? See also p. 701 ex 70-75. Also p. 710 ex 67-68. 
       <me>....</me>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <me>\boxed{....}</me>
      </p>
      </answer>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <me>\boxed{....}</me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

